<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-05-04T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-05-04T03:00:00-05:00" n="446" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d446">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4330: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-04T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">May 4, 1922—4
                                        p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received May 4—8:55
                            a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>195. My 193, May 4, 1 p.m. Wu’s forces following up their victory over
                            Chang’s forces at Changhsintien at 5 o’clock this morning occupied at
                            noon district of Fengtai on Peking-Tientsin Railway. Chang’s forces left
                            many dead and wounded and many guns behind.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>